the woman who was abandoned

28
00:01:19,800 --> 00:01:22,066
actually became one of the most revolutionary

29
00:01:22,066 --> 00:01:23,866
spiritual leaders of her time

30
00:01:24,233 --> 00:01:26,166
she didn't survive being left

31
00:01:27,166 --> 00:01:29,300
she used that pain to transform herself

32
00:01:29,300 --> 00:01:31,000
into something extraordinary

33
00:01:32,900 --> 00:01:36,066
today we're exploring the story they don't teach you

34
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:39,066
the story of Yasodhara the Buddha's wife

35
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:41,666
the woman who turned heartbreak into enlightenment

36
00:01:41,700 --> 00:01:44,500
and changed the face of spirituality forever

37
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:46,366
by the end of this video

38
00:01:46,366 --> 00:01:47,966
you'll never think about the Buddha's journey

39
00:01:47,966 --> 00:01:49,166
the same way again

40
00:01:53,966 --> 00:01:55,033
ancient India

41
00:01:55,033 --> 00:01:58,366
500 BCE in the region where India and Nepal meet

42
00:01:58,366 --> 00:01:59,166
today

43
00:01:59,500 --> 00:02:02,266
this story starts way before either of them were born

44
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:04,333
according to the Jataka tales

45
00:02:04,666 --> 00:02:07,333
these two souls were connected across lifetimes

46
00:02:07,466 --> 00:02:10,600
in one past life Yasodhara was a devoted wife

47
00:02:10,600 --> 00:02:12,966
who prayed for her husband's spiritual success

48
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:14,133
in another

49
00:02:14,466 --> 00:02:16,466
they were both seeking the path to enlightenment

50
00:02:16,466 --> 00:02:17,266
together

51
00:02:18,866 --> 00:02:20,100
some Buddhist traditions say

52
00:02:20,100 --> 00:02:21,700
their meeting wasn't coincidence

53
00:02:22,033 --> 00:02:23,966
destiny orchestrated their union

54
00:02:24,666 --> 00:02:27,200
Yasodhara wasn't your typical princess sitting around

55
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:28,500
waiting to be rescued

56
00:02:29,966 --> 00:02:31,666
born into the Shakya clan

57
00:02:31,900 --> 00:02:34,333
the same royal family as Sidhartha

58
00:02:34,633 --> 00:02:37,166
she was brilliant sharp

59
00:02:37,600 --> 00:02:39,300
the kind of woman who could hold her own

60
00:02:39,300 --> 00:02:43,133
in political discussions and philosophical debates

61
00:02:44,066 --> 00:02:45,766
the Lalitavistara Sutra

62
00:02:45,766 --> 00:02:47,933
describes their wedding as a grand affair

63
00:02:48,500 --> 00:02:50,600
but most people miss this detail

64
00:02:51,233 --> 00:02:53,266
before Sidartha could marry her

65
00:02:53,866 --> 00:02:55,166
he had to prove himself

66
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:57,333
in competitions against other suitors

67
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:00,333
archery sword fighting

68
00:03:00,666 --> 00:03:02,700
intellectual contests

69
00:03:03,266 --> 00:03:04,600
and Yasodhara

70
00:03:05,266 --> 00:03:07,066
she wasn't a prize to be won

71
00:03:07,700 --> 00:03:09,766
she was choosing her partner too

72
00:03:10,466 --> 00:03:11,933
when they finally married

73
00:03:12,066 --> 00:03:13,900
palace life seemed perfect

74
00:03:14,066 --> 00:03:17,366
gold everywhere servants attending to every need

75
00:03:17,700 --> 00:03:19,466
three palaces for different seasons

76
00:03:19,466 --> 00:03:22,300
because why not their son

77
00:03:22,333 --> 00:03:25,100
Rahula was born and for a moment

78
00:03:25,166 --> 00:03:27,200
everything looked like a fairy tale ending

79
00:03:27,633 --> 00:03:29,666
but Yasodhara was paying attention

80
00:03:29,666 --> 00:03:32,100
she noticed things late night walks

81
00:03:32,100 --> 00:03:34,700
where Siddhartha would stare at the stars for hours

82
00:03:35,033 --> 00:03:37,100
deep silences during meals

83
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:40,000
questions about suffering that came out of nowhere

84
00:03:40,366 --> 00:03:43,100
the restlessness growing in his eyes

85
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:44,366
she was intelligent

86
00:03:44,366 --> 00:03:46,066
enough to sense something was building

87
00:03:46,066 --> 00:03:50,100
but nobody not even someone as perceptive as Yasodhara

88
00:03:50,266 --> 00:03:52,166
could have predicted what was coming next

89
00:03:57,466 --> 00:03:58,766
the night it happened

90
00:03:59,433 --> 00:04:01,066
Yasodhara was sleeping peacefully

91
00:04:01,066 --> 00:04:02,900
next to her husband and baby son

92
00:04:03,766 --> 00:04:05,466
according to the Mahavastu

93
00:04:05,466 --> 00:04:07,333
one of the earliest Buddhist texts

94
00:04:07,766 --> 00:04:10,533
Siddhartha looked at his sleeping family one last time

95
00:04:10,766 --> 00:04:12,833
some versions say he almost woke her

96
00:04:12,833 --> 00:04:15,233
others claim he kissed their foreheads goodbye

97
00:04:15,233 --> 00:04:18,366
but in the end he chose silence

98
00:04:19,866 --> 00:04:21,666
he took his horse Kanthaka

99
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:23,366
his charioteer Channa

100
00:04:23,566 --> 00:04:25,500
and disappeared into the darkness

101
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:31,400
morning came Yasodhara reached across the bed empty

102
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:34,566
she called for him silence

103
00:04:34,966 --> 00:04:36,466
she ran through the palace

104
00:04:36,766 --> 00:04:40,400
asking servants guards anyone

105
00:04:40,833 --> 00:04:42,200
nobody had answers

106
00:04:42,800 --> 00:04:44,733
then the terrible truth hit her

107
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:48,100
her husband the father of her child

108
00:04:48,300 --> 00:04:51,866
the future king had vanished without a word

109
00:04:52,666 --> 00:04:54,866
feel that for a second the confusion

110
00:04:54,866 --> 00:04:56,466
the panic the embarrassment

111
00:04:56,700 --> 00:04:59,333
but this is where Yasodhara's strength shows up

112
00:04:59,366 --> 00:05:01,333
while other women might have collapsed

113
00:05:01,633 --> 00:05:04,266
she got angry really angry

114
00:05:04,700 --> 00:05:07,533
he hadn't left for war or duty or another woman

115
00:05:07,800 --> 00:05:10,300
he'd abandoned his son his people

116
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:13,666
everything they'd built together without explanation

117
00:05:13,833 --> 00:05:15,933
without purpose anyone could understand

118
00:05:17,033 --> 00:05:18,866
the palace buzzed with whispers

119
00:05:18,900 --> 00:05:21,766
neighboring kingdoms whispered captured

120
00:05:21,900 --> 00:05:25,766
mad or simply weak and Yasodhara

121
00:05:26,066 --> 00:05:28,166
she was left holding baby Rahula

122
00:05:28,200 --> 00:05:30,466
facing the judgment of an entire society

123
00:05:30,466 --> 00:05:32,900
that blamed wives when husbands disappeared

124
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:36,166
Ancient India wasn't kind to single mothers

125
00:05:36,166 --> 00:05:38,866
especially royal ones whose husbands had vanished

126
00:05:39,166 --> 00:05:40,600
instead of hiding in shame

127
00:05:41,266 --> 00:05:44,600
Yasodhara held her head high and raised Rahula alone

128
00:05:47,066 --> 00:05:48,666
years passed no letters

129
00:05:48,666 --> 00:05:51,666
no messages no confirmation he was even alive

130
00:05:51,966 --> 00:05:53,533
the woman who once had everything

131
00:05:53,700 --> 00:05:56,533
now had to rebuild her entire world from scratch

132
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:03,733
three years in four years

133
00:06:04,066 --> 00:06:05,166
five years

134
00:06:06,066 --> 00:06:06,700
Yasodhara

135
00:06:06,700 --> 00:06:08,966
had almost given up hope of ever seeing her husband

136
00:06:08,966 --> 00:06:09,766
again

137
00:06:10,300 --> 00:06:12,333
then the stories started trickling in

138
00:06:12,366 --> 00:06:14,033
merchants traveling through the kingdom

139
00:06:14,033 --> 00:06:15,300
brought strange tales

140
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:17,866
a wandering teacher somewhere near Bodh Gaya

141
00:06:18,100 --> 00:06:20,733
a man who spoke about suffering and liberation

142
00:06:21,033 --> 00:06:23,333
someone who looked familiar

143
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:25,266
at first

144
00:06:25,866 --> 00:06:27,766
Yasodhara dismissed these rumors

145
00:06:28,100 --> 00:06:30,700
dozens of spiritual teachers roamed India

146
00:06:30,766 --> 00:06:32,533
holy men were everywhere

147
00:06:32,833 --> 00:06:34,700
why would this one be different

148
00:06:34,933 --> 00:06:36,600
but something inside her had changed

149
00:06:36,600 --> 00:06:38,200
during those years of abandonment

150
00:06:38,500 --> 00:06:40,500
the luxury of palace life

151
00:06:40,666 --> 00:06:42,766
the gold the servants

152
00:06:43,166 --> 00:06:44,766
the endless ceremonies

153
00:06:45,366 --> 00:06:48,333
they all felt hollow now empty

154
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:50,800
she started visiting temples

155
00:06:50,866 --> 00:06:52,666
not for show or royal duty

156
00:06:52,700 --> 00:06:54,500
but searching for something real

157
00:06:54,633 --> 00:06:56,500
something that could explain why her perfect

158
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:57,566
life had crumbled

159
00:06:58,300 --> 00:06:59,500
then one day

160
00:06:59,566 --> 00:07:01,800
a traveling monk arrived at the palace gates

161
00:07:02,066 --> 00:07:04,266
he spoke about a teacher called the Buddha

162
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:05,966
the awakened one

163
00:07:06,633 --> 00:07:09,533
this teacher had discovered the root of all suffering

164
00:07:09,866 --> 00:07:11,966
he could explain why people hurt

165
00:07:12,233 --> 00:07:14,133
why nothing lasts forever

166
00:07:14,566 --> 00:07:16,866
why attachment brings pain

167
00:07:17,500 --> 00:07:19,733
the monk described this Buddha's background

168
00:07:20,066 --> 00:07:22,500
royal family left his palace

169
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:25,333
abandoned his wife and child to seek truth

170
00:07:25,700 --> 00:07:27,833
when the monk mentioned the teacher's background

171
00:07:27,833 --> 00:07:30,566
a prince from the Shakya clan named Siddhartha Gautama

172
00:07:30,566 --> 00:07:33,800
who had left his family Yasodhara's blood went cold

173
00:07:34,200 --> 00:07:35,666
the room started spinning

174
00:07:35,766 --> 00:07:37,066
her missing husband

175
00:07:37,200 --> 00:07:39,466
the man who'd left her without explanation

176
00:07:39,600 --> 00:07:42,533
had become the most famous spiritual teacher in India

177
00:07:43,166 --> 00:07:44,266
relief flooded through her

178
00:07:44,266 --> 00:07:46,000
first he was alive

179
00:07:46,233 --> 00:07:48,866
then came anger then confusion

180
00:07:49,233 --> 00:07:53,533
then something she hadn't expected curiosity

181
00:07:58,866 --> 00:08:00,300
The Vinaya Pitaka tells us that

182
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:02,066
six years after his enlightenment

183
00:08:02,433 --> 00:08:04,500
Buddha decided to return to his homeland

184
00:08:04,900 --> 00:08:07,533
Yasodhara heard the news before anyone else

185
00:08:07,700 --> 00:08:09,900
servants whispered about royal preparations

186
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:12,100
the king was organizing

187
00:08:12,100 --> 00:08:14,533
a massive welcome for the enlightened prince

188
00:08:14,900 --> 00:08:17,400
the entire kingdom buzzed with excitement

189
00:08:17,666 --> 00:08:19,466
everyone except Yasodhara

190
00:08:19,866 --> 00:08:22,100
she made a decision that shocked the court

191
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:24,000
while every other royal family member

192
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:25,900
rushed to greet Buddha at the city gates

193
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:27,866
she stayed in the palace

194
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:29,966
she wasn't going to run to him

195
00:08:29,966 --> 00:08:31,266
like nothing had happened

196
00:08:31,600 --> 00:08:35,400
if he wanted to see her he could come to her

197
00:08:35,866 --> 00:08:37,466
hours passed finally

198
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:39,766
footsteps approached her chamber

199
00:08:40,066 --> 00:08:42,300
the man who entered looked like Siddhartha

200
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:44,566
but different calmer

201
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:45,866
more present

202
00:08:46,300 --> 00:08:49,266
his eyes held a depth that hadn't been there before

203
00:08:49,600 --> 00:08:52,166
he wore simple robes instead of royal silk

204
00:08:52,700 --> 00:08:55,066
the ancient texts skip the personal details

205
00:08:55,066 --> 00:08:57,266
but we can imagine the weight of that moment

206
00:08:57,666 --> 00:08:59,133
years of separation

207
00:08:59,700 --> 00:09:02,266
two people who had become completely different

208
00:09:02,500 --> 00:09:03,633
he had found enlightenment

209
00:09:03,633 --> 00:09:05,366
through leaving everything behind

210
00:09:06,033 --> 00:09:09,400
she had found strength by staying and rebuilding

211
00:09:09,900 --> 00:09:13,200
both had transformed but through opposite paths

212
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:15,766
perhaps few words were needed

213
00:09:16,066 --> 00:09:18,733
just the recognition of who they'd each become

214
00:09:19,300 --> 00:09:21,966
he'd found enlightenment through renunciation

215
00:09:22,366 --> 00:09:24,466
she'd found strength through endurance

216
00:09:24,966 --> 00:09:27,900
but the reunion wasn't complete without one more person

217
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,066
their son Rahula

218
00:09:30,300 --> 00:09:31,866
now 7 years old

219
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,766
met his father for the first time since infancy

220
00:09:35,366 --> 00:09:36,266
that meeting

221
00:09:36,433 --> 00:09:39,066
that's a whole other story we'll save for another video

222
00:09:39,600 --> 00:09:41,900
the real shock came next

223
00:09:42,266 --> 00:09:44,300
after their private conversation

224
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:47,933
Yasodhara made an announcement that stunned everyone

225
00:09:48,433 --> 00:09:50,066
she wanted to join the Sangha

226
00:09:50,066 --> 00:09:52,133
the community of Buddhist practitioners

227
00:09:52,566 --> 00:09:54,033
not to follow her husband

228
00:09:54,033 --> 00:09:56,133
to follow her own path to enlightenment

229
00:10:01,433 --> 00:10:04,133
this is where Yasodhara's story gets revolutionary

230
00:10:04,300 --> 00:10:05,666
and where most history books

231
00:10:05,666 --> 00:10:07,333
conveniently skip the details

232
00:10:07,900 --> 00:10:10,600
at first Buddha refused her request

233
00:10:10,833 --> 00:10:13,366
not because he doubted her spiritual capacity

234
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:16,366
but because the Sangha only included men

235
00:10:16,633 --> 00:10:19,533
no women allowed that was the rule

236
00:10:19,866 --> 00:10:22,366
but Yasodhara wasn't the type to accept no

237
00:10:22,366 --> 00:10:26,000
quietly she teamed up with Mahapajapati Gotami

238
00:10:26,400 --> 00:10:29,766
Buddha's stepmother and a group of other royal women

239
00:10:29,866 --> 00:10:33,900
together they approached Buddha again and again

240
00:10:33,900 --> 00:10:37,466
he said no so they did something unprecedented

241
00:10:37,466 --> 00:10:40,066
they shaved their heads put on yellow robes

242
00:10:40,200 --> 00:10:42,266
and showed up at the monastery anyway

243
00:10:43,233 --> 00:10:45,566
picture the scene a group of women

244
00:10:45,700 --> 00:10:47,533
former princesses and Queens

245
00:10:47,800 --> 00:10:49,466
standing at the gates of an all male

246
00:10:49,466 --> 00:10:50,766
religious community

247
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:53,900
demanding equal access to spiritual training

248
00:10:55,033 --> 00:10:56,900
this wasn't 2024

249
00:10:56,900 --> 00:11:01,500
this was 500 BCE women challenging religious authority

250
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:04,266
unheard of finally

251
00:11:04,300 --> 00:11:06,566
after pressure from his cousin Ananda

252
00:11:07,666 --> 00:11:11,133
Buddha relented he established the Bhikkhuni Sangha

253
00:11:11,233 --> 00:11:12,733
the order of Buddhist nuns

254
00:11:13,200 --> 00:11:15,600
Yasodhara became one of the first women ever ordained

255
00:11:15,600 --> 00:11:18,666
in Buddhist tradition but she didn't stop there

256
00:11:18,866 --> 00:11:20,166
the Therigatha

257
00:11:20,166 --> 00:11:22,900
a collection of verses by early Buddhist nuns

258
00:11:23,300 --> 00:11:25,300
includes Yasodhara's own words

259
00:11:25,766 --> 00:11:29,333
listen to this I have cut off my hair

260
00:11:29,566 --> 00:11:31,400
I have put on the yellow robe

261
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:35,866
I live by alms having been a woman of great beauty

262
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:38,500
now I am free from attachment

263
00:11:39,300 --> 00:11:41,066
she wasn't celebrating becoming a nun

264
00:11:41,066 --> 00:11:43,300
because she wanted to be near her former husband

265
00:11:43,600 --> 00:11:45,033
she was celebrating her freedom

266
00:11:45,033 --> 00:11:48,266
from everything that had once defined her beauty

267
00:11:48,366 --> 00:11:51,866
marriage status royal privilege

268
00:11:52,366 --> 00:11:54,700
Yasodhara developed her own teaching style

269
00:11:55,033 --> 00:11:57,966
her own insights her own followers

270
00:11:58,766 --> 00:12:01,166
she became known for helping other women understand

271
00:12:01,166 --> 00:12:03,500
that spiritual awakening didn't require suffering

272
00:12:03,500 --> 00:12:04,366
in silence

273
00:12:05,100 --> 00:12:07,800
she taught that pain abandonment

274
00:12:07,900 --> 00:12:08,900
betrayal

275
00:12:09,433 --> 00:12:11,533
these weren't obstacles to enlightenment

276
00:12:12,100 --> 00:12:13,833
they were gateways to understanding

277
00:12:13,833 --> 00:12:16,266
the temporary nature of all relationships

278
00:12:16,466 --> 00:12:19,333
all circumstances all identities

279
00:12:21,066 --> 00:12:21,866
some traditions

280
00:12:21,866 --> 00:12:24,266
state that Yasodhara attained arahantship

281
00:12:24,300 --> 00:12:25,000
some even say

282
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:27,200
